      "message": "nit: The documentation for `SdBusError` still says that it will become the owner of the error.\n\n```\n108     /** Becomes the owner of the error */\n109     SdBusError(sd_bus_error* error, const char* prefix,\n110                SdBusInterface* intf \u003d \u0026sdbus_impl);\n```\n\nTherefore in my fix the `SdBusError` constructor frees the error passed as argument.\n\n```\n--- a/src/exception.cpp\n+++ b/src/exception.cpp\n@@ -56,6 +56,10 @@ SdBusError::SdBusError(sd_bus_error* error_in, const char* prefix,\n {\n     intf-\u003esd_bus_error_copy(\u0026error, error_in);\n \n+    // idempotent on unset and already free\u0027d errors\n+    // https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/sd_bus_error.3.html\n+    intf-\u003esd_bus_error_free(error_in);\n+\n     populateMessage(std::string(prefix));\n }\n```\n\nWith that alternative the code becomes more compact and not necessary anymore to \nhave a local variable, can directly throw it in the error path.\n\nWhat do you think, can we do it that way or did i overlooked something ?\n\nIf we solve it like PS1, do we need to update the comment for the `SdBusError` constructor?",
